    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-22T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-22T14:00:00-05:00" n="476"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d476">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00Sonora/780: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Guaymas</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bursley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guaymas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-22T13:00:00-06:00"
                            >April 22, 1929—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 23—1:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Practically entire stock fuel oil of railroad is at Guaymas and Empalme. With
                    operations of railway stopped, rebels have taken over the property and are using
                    it and all necessary supplies to further revolution movement. Strong oral
                    protest made to <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> authorities again today for the
                    protection of American interests by Commander and Consulate. If this action and
                    the taking of receipts by the company will protect Southern Pacific interests
                    with the Mexican Government recommend no further action be taken … Please repeat
                    to Embassy at Mexico City.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bursley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
